{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Ali Ashraf Darvishian | image = Darvishian.jpg | imagesize = 250px | caption = | pseudonym = Latif Talkhestani | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date |df=yes|1941|08|03}} | birth_place = [[Kermanshah]], [[Iran]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2017|10|26|1941|08|03|}} | death_place = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] | occupation = Writer | nationality = | genre = Novel, short story, biography, etc | subject = | spouse = Shahnaz Darabian | movement = [[Modernism]], [[Literary realism|Realism]], [[Socialism]] | notableworks = {{Plainlist| * ''Sal-ha-ye Abri (Cloudy Years)'' * ''Abshouran'' * ''Az In Welayat (From This Country)'' * ''Hamrah-e Ahang-ha-ye Babam (With My Father's Songs)'' * ''Afsane-ha va Matal-ha-ye Kurdi (Kurdish Legends and Fictions)'' }} | awards = {{Plainlist| * {{Awd|Gelawej Cultural Festival|2013}} }} | website = }}
'''Ali Ashraf Darvishian''' ({{lang-fa|علی‌اشرف درویشیان}}&lrm;; 25 August 1941 – 26 October 2017) was an Iranian story writer and scholar. After finishing teacher-training college, he taught at the poverty-stricken villages of Gilan-e-Gharb and Shah Abad (nowadays called Islam Abad). This atmosphere is featured in most of his stories. Later, he moved to Tehran and continued his studies in Persian literature. As of 2006, Ali Ashraf Darvishian was in [[Australia]] as a guest of the [[Iranian Centre for Democracy]] and presented a number of lectures on a broad range of social and cultural issues.
[[File:Ali-Ashraf Darwishiyan. 2.jpg|Left|thumb|Ali-Ashraf Darvishian]]
[[Marjane Satrapi]], an Iranian-French author, mentions Darvishian in her graphic novel ''Persepolis''. She considers him her favorite childhood author, recalls going to his clandestine book-signing, and describes him as "a kind of local [[Charles Dickens]]".<ref>[[Marjane Satrapi|Satrapi, Marjane]]. ''The Complete Persepolis''. ''[[Pantheon Books]]''. 30 October 2007. 33. {{ISBN|0-375-71483-9}}, {{ISBN|978-0-375-71483-2}}</ref> He died at a hospital in Tehran, on 26 October 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=علی‌اشرف درویشیان درگذشت|url=http://www.bbc.com/persian/arts-41765772|accessdate=26 October 2017|work=BBC Persian}}</ref>
