'''Brooklyn "Brookie" Supreme''' (April 12, 1928 – September 6, 1948){{efn|''Guinness Book of World Records'' states April 12, 1928 – September 6, 1948.<ref name= Guinness1988 /> Many sources list no exact birthdate but state the years 1928<ref name= green19>{{cite book |page= 19 |title=The Belgian Horse |first= Sara |last= Green|publisher= Bellwether Media| date= August 1, 2009| isbn= 9781612115955}}</ref>–1948.<ref name=Equus>{{cite journal| title= [Unknown]| work= Equus| number= 251–254| volume= | publisher= Equine Health Publications Company| year= 1998| url= | page= 24 }}</ref> Strangely, the source with the most specific information (including an ancestor, foaling location, dates, and original ownership) indicates June 6, 1930 – 1950,<ref name= Empire>{{cite book| title= The Empire of Equus| first= David P.| last= Willoughby| publisher= A. S. Barnes| year= 1974|isbn= 9780498010477}}</ref> but another source states that the horse placed "First in Yearling Stallion class and Reserve Junior Champion at the 1929 Iowa State Fair."<ref name= century>{{cite book| title= A century of Belgian horses in America| chapter= Brooklyn Supreme — The Largest Horse| first= Maurice| last= Telleen| publisher= M. B. Telleen| year= 1991| isbn= 9780962907609}}</ref>}} was a [[roan (horse)|red roan]]<ref name= Empire /> [[Belgian horse|Belgian]] [[stallion]] noted for his extreme size. Although disputed, the horse may be the world record holder for largest (but not tallest) horse<ref name=Equus /><ref name= Mason>{{cite encyclopedia| title= American Belgian Draft (USA)| work= Mason's World Encyclopedia of Livestock Breeds and Breeding| first1= Valerie | last1= Porter| first2= Lawrence | last2= Alderson| first3= Stephen J. G. | last3= Hall| first4= D. Phillip | last4= Sponenberg |publisher= CABI| year= 2016 | isbn= 9781845934668| page= 434| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=2UEJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA434&lpg=PA434&dq=Brooklyn+Supreme,+a+Belgian+horse+who+lived+in+Iowa&source=bl&ots=8_84JnDpD3&sig=Fp1SOHeRR4HMFSpY_Ncjq2wdsao&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiU95iEwJDSAhUG64MKHaZ7CGA4ChDoAQgZMAA#v=onepage&q=Brooklyn%20Supreme&f=false| access-date= February 14, 2017}}</ref> and was designated the world's heaviest horse.<ref name= Gentle37>{{cite book| title= The Gentle Giants: The Story of Draft Horses| first= Stanley M.| last= Jepsen| publisher= Arco| year= 1973| isbn= 9780668027656}}</ref><ref name= Guinness1988>{{cite encyclopedia| work= Guinness Book of World Records| title= World's Heaviest Horse| page= 43| edition= 1988| first= Norris| last= McWhirter| editor-first1= Alan| editor-last1= Russel| editor-first2= David A. | editor-last2= Boehm| publisher= Sterling Publishing Company| year= 1987| isbn= 9780806965987}}</ref> He stood 19.2 [[Hand (unit)|hands]] ({{convert|198|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}) tall and weighed {{convert|3200|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} with a girth of {{convert|10|ft|2|in|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book |page=39 |title=The Strongest Animals in the World Are Herbivores |first=Paul E. |last=Widmayer |location= Bloomington, Indiana |publisher= West Bow Press |year= 2014| isbn= 9781490826806}}</ref><ref name= RH>{{cite web | publisher = [[Rural Heritage]] | website= RuralHeritage.com| | title = Picture of Brooklyn Supreme | url = http://www.ruralheritage.com/horse_paddock/horse_large_bs.htm}}</ref><ref name=Ult>{{cite web |url=http://ultimatehorsesite.com/info/worldstallesthorse.html |title=The World's Biggest, Tallest, Largest Horses |accessdate=23 October 2010| website= ultimatehorsesite.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111129200719/http://www.ultimatehorsesite.com/info/worldstallesthorse.html| first= Annamaria| last= Tadlock| archivedate= November 29, 2011 | deadurl= yes}}</ref><ref name= green19 /> His horseshoes required {{convert|30|in|cm|abbr=on}} of iron.<ref name= RH /><ref name= GentleSS>{{cite web| url= http://www.stallionstation.com/gentlegiants/photos.html| website= StallionStation.com| title= The Gentle Giants II| date= | access-date= February 14, 2017}}</ref>
The horse was foaled on the [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]] farm of Earle Brown,<ref name= Empire /> who first exhibited him.<ref name= century /> Before becoming oversized, the stallion "had been Grand Champion of his breed in many state fairs".<ref name= Empire /> One of his great-grandfathers was another famous horse, Farceur 7332.<ref name= Empire />
For much of his fame, Brooklyn Supreme was owned by Charles Grant Good of [[Ogden, Iowa|Ogden]], [[Iowa]]; Ralph M. Fogleman of [[Callender, Iowa]] partnered with Good and exhibited the horse around the US,<ref name= Gentle37 /> charging spectators 10 cents to view the animal.<ref name= GentleSS />
