{{speciesbox |image = |status = CR |status_system = IUCN3.1 |status_ref = <ref name=iucn_status>{{cite journal |author=Shaw, K. |author2=Roy, S. |author3=Wilson, B. |last-author-amp=yes |title=''Carpinus putoensis'' |journal=[[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] |volume=2014 |page=e.T32303A2813038 |publisher=[[IUCN]] |date=2014 |url=http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/32303/0 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2014-3.RLTS.T32303A2813038.en |access-date=10 November 2017}}</ref> |genus = Carpinus |species = putoensis |authority = Cheng }}
'''''Carpinus putoensis''''' ('''Putuo hornbeam''', {{zh|c=普陀鹅耳枥}}) is a species of [[plant]] in the [[Corylaceae]] family. It is a small tree, up to {{convert|15|m}} tall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=601&taxon_id=200006196 |title=''Carpinus putoensis'' |author=eFloras |work=Flora of China |publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden, St. Louis, MO & Harvard University Herbaria, Cambridge, MA |accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>
It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Zhoushan]] archipelago in [[China]] where it survives as a single tree on [[Putuoshan|Putuo Island]]. It is [[monoecious]], thereby in principle still able to reproduce sexually in the wild.<ref name=IUCN>{{IUCN| id = 32303| taxon = ''Carpinus putoensis''| assessor = World Conservation Monitoring Centre| assessment_year = 1998| version = 2011.2| accessdate = 11 April 2012}}</ref> According to [[Edward O. Wilson]], this is an example of what [[conservation biologist]]s call "living dead" species.
